summary: Email correspondence between prosecutors regarding the status of subpoenas served to multiple airlines and Expedia for travel records related to Ghislaine Maxwell. The emails discuss compliance issues, missing identifiers, and follow-up efforts to obtain the requested information.

persons.name: Assistant United States Attorney
persons.context: The sender of the email correspondence, working in the Southern District of New York, coordinating the service of subpoenas for travel records related to Ghislaine Maxwell.

keyFacts: Prosecutors were actively subpoenaing travel records from multiple airlines (United, American, Delta, Alaska, Southwest, JetBlue) and Expedia as part of the investigation into Ghislaine Maxwell.
Expedia required additional identifiers like email addresses, credit card numbers, or itinerary numbers because their databases lacked date of birth information to identify customers.
JetBlue was not served because prosecutors had not confirmed confidentiality with them, and it was noted that JetBlue did not begin flying until 2000.
The subpoenas were served via legal process handlers, with Expedia requiring service through National Registered Agents, Inc. at a CT Corp office in New York.
Prosecutors were under timing pressure to obtain the airline records before traveling to California for the investigation.
